course_name: Human Behavior and the Social Environment
description: The person-in-environment, bio-psycho-social perspective is the lens through which theories of personality, family, group, organization, community, culture and their interactions are explored. (Duplicates credit in SOWK 503 and SOWK 505)

course_name: Professional Self-Care in Integrative Social Work Practice
description: Focuses on the value, examination and integration of professional self-care, wellness and resilience strategies into ethical and professional integrative social work practice.

course_name: Critical Decision Making in Integrative Social Work Practice
description: Focuses on the value and application of critical thinking and decision-making into ethical and professional integrative social work practice.

course_name: Foundations of Integrative Social Work Practice I
description: Principles underlying social work practice with emphasis on rapport building, engagement, assessment and contracting individuals, families and groups though a framework of social justice.

course_name: Foundations of Integrative Social Work Practice II
description: Principles underlying social work practice with emphasis on intervention, termination and evaluation with individuals, families and groups though a framework of social justice

course_name: Policy and Advocacy in Professional Social Work
description: A study of the complex and interconnecting systems of policy, programs and communities that directly and indirectly impact Social Workers' clients lives. (Duplicates credit in SOWK 534)

course_name: Science of Social Work
description: Introduction to the role of scientific inquiry in advancing social work goals. Inspires students to include science in their social work identity and professional decision-making. (Duplicates credit in SOWK 562)

course_name: Applied Learning in Practicum Education I
description: Supervised beginning generalist practicum seminar and placement to develop practice skills in working with individuals, families, groups, communities and/or organizations.

course_name: Applied Learning in Practicum Education II
description: Supervised generalist master's level practicum seminar and placement to develop practice skills in working with individuals, families, groups, communities and/or organizations.

course_name: Research and Critical Analysis for Social Work with Children and Families
description: Critical analysis and application of various data, information, and evidence to understand client problems and service needs, identify appropriate interventions, and evaluate practice decisions. Prerequisite: SOWK 506, SOWK 536, SOWK 544, SOWK 546. (Duplicates credit in SOWK 603)

course_name: Introduction to Social Work Practice with Children, Youth and Families
description: Understanding development of children and families from birth to adolescence and the developmental difficulties from an ecological perspective. Assessment/engagement of families and Interventions are introduced. Prerequisite: SOWK 506, SOWK 536, SOWK 544, SOWK 546.

course_name: Assessment and Diagnosis of Mental Disorders
description: Assessment of mental disorders, and the rationale and organization of the system for diagnosis. Emphasis is on developing differential diagnostic skills.

course_name: Social Work Practice with Children and Families in Early and
description: Provides understanding of the development of problems in early childhood, and skills for engagement, assessment, intervention, and evaluation of effectiveness for treatment of these problems.

course_name: Social Work Practice in School Settings
description: Based on ecosystems perspectives, this course examines policies, theories and principles for social work practice in school settings.

course_name: Brief Therapy and Crisis Intervention
description: Theory and multimodal approaches for brief therapy and crisis intervention with diverse clientele in a range of mental health and health settings.

course_name: Substance Related and Behavioral Addictive Disorders and Rec
description: Causal exploration of substance related and behavioral addictive disorders. Evidence-based and practice informed treatment models for vulnerable individuals, groups and families.

course_name: Social Work Practice with Adolescents, Young Adults and their Families
description: Intervention with adolescents, young adults and addressing their developmental problems, challenges and solutions. Engagement and evidence based intervention in working with youth will be covered.

course_name: Social Work in Juvenile Justice Settings
description: Provides orientation to the context and operations of juvenile justice systems, and advanced skills for social work practitioners working with youth, families and communities.

course_name: Policy and Macro Practice in Child, Youth and Family Services
description: Provides context and preparation for social work practitioners holding policy, management and macro practice roles in communities and organizations serving children, youth and families. Prerequisite: SOWK 506, SOWK 536, SOWK 544, SOWK 546.

course_name: Diversity, Social Justice and Interculturally Competent Soci
description: Introduction to diversity and social justice in the context of social work practice. Enhance intercultural competence by raising awareness of one's own values/assumptions/biases.

course_name: Life in the US Military: Foundations of Practice in Military
description: Examines the experience of military service, including challenges and theoretical and empirical foundations of military social work clinical practice.

course_name: Policy Advocacy and Social Change
description: Analysis of efforts to improve local human services organizations and agencies with consideration of political, social, demographic and organization contexts. Prerequisite: SOWK 506, SOWK 536, SOWK 544, SOWK 546.

course_name: Clinical Practice with the Military Family
description: Theoretical and practical approaches to clinical practice with military families. Overview of common social issues in the military system and demands on the family dynamic.

course_name: Social Work Practice in Integrated Care Settingss
description: Social work processes and skills required for the implementation of short-term interventions in medical, behavioral health and integrated care settings with individuals, families and groups.

course_name: Advanced Practice with Complex Social Work Cases
description: Introduction to advanced practice concepts essential to understanding engagement, assessment and diagnosis with complex social work cases from a meta-framework perspective.

course_name: Consultation, Coaching, and Social Entrepreneurship
description: Expanding roles that social workers perform within both non-profit and for-profit corporations.

course_name: Grant Writing and Program Development for Social Workers
description: Grant writing and program development that are generalized to any settings and relevant to direct and macro social work practice expertise.

course_name: Domestic and Intimate Partner Abuse
description: Recognition of domestic and intimate partner abuse and examination of effective intervention measures and preventive methods.

course_name: Applied Learning In Practicum Education III
description: Supervised practicum seminar and placement to develop practice skills in working with individuals, families, groups, communities and/or organizations.

course_name: Loss, Grief and Bereavement
description: Focus on the experiences of loss, death and bereavement as it is viewed by individuals, families and loved ones.

course_name: Applied Learning in Practicum Education IV
description: Supervised practicum seminar and placement to develop practice skills in working with individuals, families, groups, communities and/or organizations.

course_name: Group Psychotherapy in Mental Health Settings
description: Focus on group therapy for clinical social workers as practiced in various mental health settings. The entire process of group development is examined.

course_name: Integrative Learning for Advanced Social Work Practice
description: Advanced integrative learning builds on 698A by incorporating field experiences, case/best practices consultations, and dialogical inquiry on micro, mezzo, and macro practice levels. Concurrent enrollment: SOWK 699b. Graded IP/CR/NC.

course_name: Advanced Applied Learning in Practicum Education
description: Advanced supervised practicum education where students practice social work skills and apply evidence-based interventions, including some that are specific to their academic department.

course_name: Strategic Innovations for the Grand Challenges
description: Grand Challenge initiatives and interventions from diverse perspectives are explored. Multidisciplinary strategies of innovation are analyzed to effect broad-based opportunities and barriers to change.

course_name: Leading Public Discourse
description: Leading public discourse for the purposes of increasing civic engagement and public participation, building broad based public support and enabling competencies.

course_name: Leading and Managing Large Complex Systems
description: Examining large scale national, state and local intervention programs as well as modeling potential organizational redesign to improve service delivery strategies.

course_name: Financial Management for Social Change
description: Senior financial management and planning in human service organizations, emphasizing fiscal approaches that focus on strategy, including how to maximize revenue, control costs, allocate resources, improve decision-making and support successful social programs and disruptive social change.

course_name: Design Laboratory for Social Innovation I
description: Integrates design thinking with a norms-driven approach for social innovation. Students will diagnose social norms and apply design-thinking techniques to develop design criteria.

course_name: The Application of Implementation Science
description: Introduction to doctoral level research and evaluation, introducing concepts of effectively using literature, formulating a problem for research and effectively identifying a research or evaluative approach.

course_name: Executive Leadership: Leaders as Maestros
description: The Leader/Maestro Concept enlarges the student from a virtuoso perspective - individual performance - to include an organizational performance in leading, creating and measuring change.

course_name: Communication and Influence for Social Good
description: Explores how communication and new information technology influence decision-makers and the general public to address the Grand Challenges in the interest of the public good.

course_name: Data Driven Decision Making in Social Services
description: Practical introduction to using quantitative administrative data to identify trends, track performance, evaluate programs and drive decision making.

course_name: Design Laboratory for Social Innovation II
description: Continues the exploration of design thinking and norms-driven innovation. Students will design and test innovative solutions through the creation of prototypes and design labs.

course_name: Preparatory Scholarship for Capstone
description: Design and develop an innovative, feasible, and defensible Capstone Project focusing on a selected Grand Challenge for Social Work.

course_name: Preparatory Scholarship for Capstone
description: Refine a fully implementable, innovatively designed Grand Challenge Capstone Project. Future-focused on garnering support, piloting and launching students' capstone prototype.

course_name: Preparatory Scholarship for Capstone
description: Complete a fully implementable, innovatively designed Grand Challenge Capstone Project. Future-focused on garnering support, piloting and launching students' capstone project.

course_name: Research
description: Research leading to the doctorate. Maximum units which may be applied to the degree to be determined by the department. Graded CR/NC.
